=== CST ===
DOCUMENT@0..12446 {
  SUMMARY@0..59 {
    TEXT_LINE: "Use non-linear least squares to fit a function, f, to data."@0..59
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@59..60
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@60..61
  EXTENDED_SUMMARY@61..105 {
    TEXT_LINE: "Assumes ``ydata = f(xdata, *params) + eps``."@61..105
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@105..106
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@106..107
  SECTION@107..4862 {
    SECTION_HEADER@107..128 {
      NAME: "Parameters"@107..117
      NEWLINE: "\n"@117..118
      UNDERLINE: "----------"@118..128
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@128..129
    ENTRY@129..303 {
      NAME: "f"@129..130
      WHITESPACE: " "@130..131
      COLON: ":"@131..132
      WHITESPACE: " "@132..133
      TYPE: "callable"@133..141
      NEWLINE: "\n"@141..142
      WHITESPACE: "    "@142..146
      DESCRIPTION@146..303 {
        TEXT_LINE: "The model function, f(x, ...). It must take the independent"@146..205
        NEWLINE: "\n"@205..206
        WHITESPACE: "    "@206..210
        TEXT_LINE: "variable as the first argument and the parameters to fit as"@210..269
        NEWLINE: "\n"@269..270
        WHITESPACE: "    "@270..274
        TEXT_LINE: "separate remaining arguments."@274..303
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@303..304
    ENTRY@304..564 {
      NAME: "xdata"@304..309
      WHITESPACE: " "@309..310
      COLON: ":"@310..311
      WHITESPACE: " "@311..312
      TYPE: "array_like"@312..322
      NEWLINE: "\n"@322..323
      WHITESPACE: "    "@323..327
      DESCRIPTION@327..564 {
        TEXT_LINE: "The independent variable where the data is measured."@327..379
        NEWLINE: "\n"@379..380
        WHITESPACE: "    "@380..384
        TEXT_LINE: "Should usually be an M-length sequence or an (k,M)-shaped array for"@384..451
        NEWLINE: "\n"@451..452
        WHITESPACE: "    "@452..456
        TEXT_LINE: "functions with k predictors, and each element should be float"@456..517
        NEWLINE: "\n"@517..518
        WHITESPACE: "    "@518..522
        TEXT_LINE: "convertible if it is an array like object."@522..564
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@564..565
    ENTRY@565..655 {
      NAME: "ydata"@565..570
      WHITESPACE: " "@570..571
      COLON: ":"@571..572
      WHITESPACE: " "@572..573
      TYPE: "array_like"@573..583
      NEWLINE: "\n"@583..584
      WHITESPACE: "    "@584..588
      DESCRIPTION@588..655 {
        TEXT_LINE: "The dependent data, a length M array - nominally ``f(xdata, ...)``."@588..655
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@655..656
    ENTRY@656..909 {
      NAME: "p0"@656..658
      WHITESPACE: " "@658..659
      COLON: ":"@659..660
      WHITESPACE: " "@660..661
      TYPE: "array_like"@661..671
      COMMA: ","@671..672
      WHITESPACE: " "@672..673
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@673..681
      NEWLINE: "\n"@681..682
      WHITESPACE: "    "@682..686
      DESCRIPTION@686..909 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Initial guess for the parameters (length N). If None, then the"@686..748
        NEWLINE: "\n"@748..749
        WHITESPACE: "    "@749..753
        TEXT_LINE: "initial values will all be 1 (if the number of parameters for the"@753..818
        NEWLINE: "\n"@818..819
        WHITESPACE: "    "@819..823
        TEXT_LINE: "function can be determined using introspection, otherwise a"@823..882
        NEWLINE: "\n"@882..883
        WHITESPACE: "    "@883..887
        TEXT_LINE: "ValueError is raised)."@887..909
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@909..910
    ENTRY@910..1606 {
      NAME: "sigma"@910..915
      WHITESPACE: " "@915..916
      COLON: ":"@916..917
      WHITESPACE: " "@917..918
      TYPE: "None or scalar or M-length sequence or MxM array"@918..966
      COMMA: ","@966..967
      WHITESPACE: " "@967..968
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@968..976
      NEWLINE: "\n"@976..977
      WHITESPACE: "    "@977..981
      DESCRIPTION@981..1606 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Determines the uncertainty in `ydata`. If we define residuals as"@981..1045
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1045..1046
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1046..1050
        TEXT_LINE: "``r = ydata - f(xdata, *popt)``, then the interpretation of `sigma`"@1050..1117
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1117..1118
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1118..1122
        TEXT_LINE: "depends on its number of dimensions:"@1122..1158
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1158..1159
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1159..1160
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1160..1164
        TEXT_LINE: "- A scalar or 1-D `sigma` should contain values of standard deviations of"@1164..1237
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1237..1238
        WHITESPACE: "      "@1238..1244
        TEXT_LINE: "errors in `ydata`. In this case, the optimized function is"@1244..1302
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1302..1303
        WHITESPACE: "      "@1303..1309
        TEXT_LINE: "``chisq = sum((r / sigma) ** 2)``."@1309..1343
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1343..1344
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1344..1345
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1345..1349
        TEXT_LINE: "- A 2-D `sigma` should contain the covariance matrix of"@1349..1404
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1404..1405
        WHITESPACE: "      "@1405..1411
        TEXT_LINE: "errors in `ydata`. In this case, the optimized function is"@1411..1469
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1469..1470
        WHITESPACE: "      "@1470..1476
        TEXT_LINE: "``chisq = r.T @ inv(sigma) @ r``."@1476..1509
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1509..1510
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1510..1511
        WHITESPACE: "      "@1511..1517
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 0.19"@1517..1539
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1539..1540
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1540..1541
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1541..1545
        TEXT_LINE: "None (default) is equivalent of 1-D `sigma` filled with ones."@1545..1606
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@1606..1607
    ENTRY@1607..2327 {
      NAME: "absolute_sigma"@1607..1621
      WHITESPACE: " "@1621..1622
      COLON: ":"@1622..1623
      WHITESPACE: " "@1623..1624
      TYPE: "bool"@1624..1628
      COMMA: ","@1628..1629
      WHITESPACE: " "@1629..1630
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@1630..1638
      NEWLINE: "\n"@1638..1639
      WHITESPACE: "    "@1639..1643
      DESCRIPTION@1643..2327 {
        TEXT_LINE: "If True, `sigma` is used in an absolute sense and the estimated parameter"@1643..1716
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1716..1717
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1717..1721
        TEXT_LINE: "covariance `pcov` reflects these absolute values."@1721..1770
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1770..1771
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@1771..1772
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1772..1776
        TEXT_LINE: "If False (default), only the relative magnitudes of the `sigma` values matter."@1776..1854
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1854..1855
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1855..1859
        TEXT_LINE: "The returned parameter covariance matrix `pcov` is based on scaling"@1859..1926
        NEWLINE: "\n"@1926..1927
        WHITESPACE: "    "@1927..1931
        TEXT_LINE: "`sigma` by a constant factor. This constant is set by demanding that the"@1931..2003
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2003..2004
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2004..2008
        TEXT_LINE: "reduced `chisq` for the optimal parameters `popt` when using the"@2008..2072
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2072..2073
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2073..2077
        TEXT_LINE: "*scaled* `sigma` equals unity. In other words, `sigma` is scaled to"@2077..2144
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2144..2145
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2145..2149
        TEXT_LINE: "match the sample variance of the residuals after the fit. Default is False."@2149..2224
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2224..2225
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2225..2229
        TEXT_LINE: "Mathematically,"@2229..2244
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2244..2245
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2245..2249
        TEXT_LINE: "``pcov(absolute_sigma=False) = pcov(absolute_sigma=True) * chisq(popt)/(M-N)``"@2249..2327
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2327..2328
    ENTRY@2328..2669 {
      NAME: "check_finite"@2328..2340
      WHITESPACE: " "@2340..2341
      COLON: ":"@2341..2342
      WHITESPACE: " "@2342..2343
      TYPE: "bool"@2343..2347
      COMMA: ","@2347..2348
      WHITESPACE: " "@2348..2349
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@2349..2357
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2357..2358
      WHITESPACE: "    "@2358..2362
      DESCRIPTION@2362..2669 {
        TEXT_LINE: "If True, check that the input arrays do not contain nans of infs,"@2362..2427
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2427..2428
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2428..2432
        TEXT_LINE: "and raise a ValueError if they do. Setting this parameter to"@2432..2492
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2492..2493
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2493..2497
        TEXT_LINE: "False may silently produce nonsensical results if the input arrays"@2497..2563
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2563..2564
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2564..2568
        TEXT_LINE: "do contain nans. Default is True if `nan_policy` is not specified"@2568..2633
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2633..2634
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2634..2638
        TEXT_LINE: "explicitly and False otherwise."@2638..2669
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@2669..2670
    ENTRY@2670..3190 {
      NAME: "bounds"@2670..2676
      WHITESPACE: " "@2676..2677
      COLON: ":"@2677..2678
      WHITESPACE: " "@2678..2679
      TYPE: "2-tuple of array_like or `Bounds`"@2679..2712
      COMMA: ","@2712..2713
      WHITESPACE: " "@2713..2714
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@2714..2722
      NEWLINE: "\n"@2722..2723
      WHITESPACE: "    "@2723..2727
      DESCRIPTION@2727..3190 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Lower and upper bounds on parameters. Defaults to no bounds."@2727..2787
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2787..2788
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2788..2792
        TEXT_LINE: "There are two ways to specify the bounds:"@2792..2833
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2833..2834
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2834..2835
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2835..2839
        TEXT_LINE: "- Instance of `Bounds` class."@2839..2868
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2868..2869
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@2869..2870
        WHITESPACE: "    "@2870..2874
        TEXT_LINE: "- 2-tuple of array_like: Each element of the tuple must be either"@2874..2939
        NEWLINE: "\n"@2939..2940
        WHITESPACE: "      "@2940..2946
        TEXT_LINE: "an array with the length equal to the number of parameters, or a"@2946..3010
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3010..3011
        WHITESPACE: "      "@3011..3017
        TEXT_LINE: "scalar (in which case the bound is taken to be the same for all"@3017..3080
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3080..3081
        WHITESPACE: "      "@3081..3087
        TEXT_LINE: "parameters). Use ``np.inf`` with an appropriate sign to disable"@3087..3150
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3150..3151
        WHITESPACE: "      "@3151..3157
        TEXT_LINE: "bounds on all or some parameters."@3157..3190
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@3190..3191
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@3191..3192
    ENTRY@3192..3564 {
      NAME: "method"@3192..3198
      WHITESPACE: " "@3198..3199
      COLON: ":"@3199..3200
      WHITESPACE: " "@3200..3201
      TYPE: "{'lm', 'trf', 'dogbox'}"@3201..3224
      COMMA: ","@3224..3225
      WHITESPACE: " "@3225..3226
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@3226..3234
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3234..3235
      WHITESPACE: "    "@3235..3239
      DESCRIPTION@3239..3564 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Method to use for optimization. See `least_squares` for more details."@3239..3308
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3308..3309
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3309..3313
        TEXT_LINE: "Default is 'lm' for unconstrained problems and 'trf' if `bounds` are"@3313..3381
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3381..3382
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3382..3386
        TEXT_LINE: "provided. The method 'lm' won't work when the number of observations"@3386..3454
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3454..3455
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3455..3459
        TEXT_LINE: "is less than the number of variables, use 'trf' or 'dogbox' in this"@3459..3526
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3526..3527
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3527..3531
        TEXT_LINE: "case."@3531..3536
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3536..3537
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@3537..3538
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3538..3542
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 0.17"@3542..3564
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@3564..3565
    ENTRY@3565..4041 {
      NAME: "jac"@3565..3568
      WHITESPACE: " "@3568..3569
      COLON: ":"@3569..3570
      WHITESPACE: " "@3570..3571
      TYPE: "callable, str or None"@3571..3592
      COMMA: ","@3592..3593
      WHITESPACE: " "@3593..3594
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@3594..3602
      NEWLINE: "\n"@3602..3603
      WHITESPACE: "    "@3603..3607
      DESCRIPTION@3607..4041 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Function with signature ``jac(x, ...)`` which computes the Jacobian"@3607..3674
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3674..3675
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3675..3679
        TEXT_LINE: "matrix of the model function with respect to parameters as a dense"@3679..3745
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3745..3746
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3746..3750
        TEXT_LINE: "array_like structure. It will be scaled according to provided `sigma`."@3750..3820
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3820..3821
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3821..3825
        TEXT_LINE: "If None (default), the Jacobian will be estimated numerically."@3825..3887
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3887..3888
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3888..3892
        TEXT_LINE: "String keywords for 'trf' and 'dogbox' methods can be used to select"@3892..3960
        NEWLINE: "\n"@3960..3961
        WHITESPACE: "    "@3961..3965
        TEXT_LINE: "a finite difference scheme, see `least_squares`."@3965..4013
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4013..4014
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4014..4015
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4015..4019
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 0.18"@4019..4041
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@4041..4042
    ENTRY@4042..4191 {
      NAME: "full_output"@4042..4053
      WHITESPACE: " "@4053..4054
      COLON: ":"@4054..4055
      WHITESPACE: " "@4055..4056
      TYPE: "bool"@4056..4060
      COMMA: ","@4060..4061
      WHITESPACE: " "@4061..4062
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@4062..4070
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4070..4071
      WHITESPACE: "    "@4071..4075
      DESCRIPTION@4075..4191 {
        TEXT_LINE: "If True, this function returns additional information: `infodict`,"@4075..4141
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4141..4142
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4142..4146
        TEXT_LINE: "`mesg`, and `ier`."@4146..4164
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4164..4165
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4165..4166
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4166..4170
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 1.9"@4170..4191
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@4191..4192
    ENTRY@4192..4757 {
      NAME: "nan_policy"@4192..4202
      WHITESPACE: " "@4202..4203
      COLON: ":"@4203..4204
      WHITESPACE: " "@4204..4205
      TYPE: "{'raise', 'omit', None}"@4205..4228
      COMMA: ","@4228..4229
      WHITESPACE: " "@4229..4230
      OPTIONAL: "optional"@4230..4238
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4238..4239
      WHITESPACE: "    "@4239..4243
      DESCRIPTION@4243..4757 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Defines how to handle when input contains nan."@4243..4289
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4289..4290
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4290..4294
        TEXT_LINE: "The following options are available (default is None):"@4294..4348
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4348..4349
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4349..4350
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4350..4354
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'raise': throws an error"@4354..4380
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4380..4381
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4381..4385
        TEXT_LINE: "* 'omit': performs the calculations ignoring nan values"@4385..4440
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4440..4441
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4441..4445
        TEXT_LINE: "* None: no special handling of NaNs is performed"@4445..4493
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4493..4494
        WHITESPACE: "      "@4494..4500
        TEXT_LINE: "(except what is done by check_finite); the behavior when NaNs"@4500..4561
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4561..4562
        WHITESPACE: "      "@4562..4568
        TEXT_LINE: "are present is implementation-dependent and may change."@4568..4623
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4623..4624
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4624..4625
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4625..4629
        TEXT_LINE: "Note that if this value is specified explicitly (not None),"@4629..4688
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4688..4689
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4689..4693
        TEXT_LINE: "`check_finite` will be set as False."@4693..4729
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4729..4730
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4730..4731
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4731..4735
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 1.11"@4735..4757
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@4757..4758
    ENTRY@4758..4862 {
      NAME: "**kwargs"@4758..4766
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4766..4767
      WHITESPACE: "    "@4767..4771
      DESCRIPTION@4771..4862 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Keyword arguments passed to `leastsq` for ``method='lm'`` or"@4771..4831
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4831..4832
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4832..4836
        TEXT_LINE: "`least_squares` otherwise."@4836..4862
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@4862..4863
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@4863..4864
  SECTION@4864..7670 {
    SECTION_HEADER@4864..4879 {
      NAME: "Returns"@4864..4871
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4871..4872
      UNDERLINE: "-------"@4872..4879
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@4879..4880
    ENTRY@4880..5020 {
      NAME: "popt"@4880..4884
      WHITESPACE: " "@4884..4885
      COLON: ":"@4885..4886
      WHITESPACE: " "@4886..4887
      TYPE: "array"@4887..4892
      NEWLINE: "\n"@4892..4893
      WHITESPACE: "    "@4893..4897
      DESCRIPTION@4897..5020 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Optimal values for the parameters so that the sum of the squared"@4897..4961
        NEWLINE: "\n"@4961..4962
        WHITESPACE: "    "@4962..4966
        TEXT_LINE: "residuals of ``f(xdata, *popt) - ydata`` is minimized."@4966..5020
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@5020..5021
    ENTRY@5021..6057 {
      NAME: "pcov"@5021..5025
      WHITESPACE: " "@5025..5026
      COLON: ":"@5026..5027
      WHITESPACE: " "@5027..5028
      TYPE: "2-D array"@5028..5037
      NEWLINE: "\n"@5037..5038
      WHITESPACE: "    "@5038..5042
      DESCRIPTION@5042..6057 {
        TEXT_LINE: "The estimated approximate covariance of popt. The diagonals provide"@5042..5109
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5109..5110
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5110..5114
        TEXT_LINE: "the variance of the parameter estimate. To compute one standard"@5114..5177
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5177..5178
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5178..5182
        TEXT_LINE: "deviation errors on the parameters, use"@5182..5221
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5221..5222
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5222..5226
        TEXT_LINE: "``perr = np.sqrt(np.diag(pcov))``. Note that the relationship between"@5226..5295
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5295..5296
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5296..5300
        TEXT_LINE: "`cov` and parameter error estimates is derived based on a linear"@5300..5364
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5364..5365
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5365..5369
        TEXT_LINE: "approximation to the model function around the optimum [1]_."@5369..5429
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5429..5430
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5430..5434
        TEXT_LINE: "When this approximation becomes inaccurate, `cov` may not provide an"@5434..5502
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5502..5503
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5503..5507
        TEXT_LINE: "accurate measure of uncertainty."@5507..5539
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5539..5540
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@5540..5541
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5541..5545
        TEXT_LINE: "How the `sigma` parameter affects the estimated covariance"@5545..5603
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5603..5604
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5604..5608
        TEXT_LINE: "depends on `absolute_sigma` argument, as described above."@5608..5665
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5665..5666
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@5666..5667
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5667..5671
        TEXT_LINE: "If the Jacobian matrix at the solution doesn't have a full rank, then"@5671..5740
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5740..5741
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5741..5745
        TEXT_LINE: "'lm' method returns a matrix filled with ``np.inf``, on the other hand"@5745..5815
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5815..5816
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5816..5820
        TEXT_LINE: "'trf'  and 'dogbox' methods use Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse to compute"@5820..5890
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5890..5891
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5891..5895
        TEXT_LINE: "the covariance matrix. Covariance matrices with large condition numbers"@5895..5966
        NEWLINE: "\n"@5966..5967
        WHITESPACE: "    "@5967..5971
        TEXT_LINE: "(e.g. computed with `numpy.linalg.cond`) may indicate that results are"@5971..6041
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6041..6042
        WHITESPACE: "    "@6042..6046
        TEXT_LINE: "unreliable."@6046..6057
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@6057..6058
    ENTRY@6058..7253 {
      NAME: "infodict"@6058..6066
      WHITESPACE: " "@6066..6067
      COLON: ":"@6067..6068
      WHITESPACE: " "@6068..6069
      TYPE: "dict (returned only if `full_output` is True)"@6069..6114
      NEWLINE: "\n"@6114..6115
      WHITESPACE: "    "@6115..6119
      DESCRIPTION@6119..7253 {
        TEXT_LINE: "a dictionary of optional outputs with the keys:"@6119..6166
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6166..6167
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@6167..6168
        WHITESPACE: "    "@6168..6172
        TEXT_LINE: "``nfev``"@6172..6180
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6180..6181
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6181..6189
        TEXT_LINE: "The number of function calls. Methods 'trf' and 'dogbox' do not"@6189..6252
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6252..6253
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6253..6261
        TEXT_LINE: "count function calls for numerical Jacobian approximation,"@6261..6319
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6319..6320
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6320..6328
        TEXT_LINE: "as opposed to 'lm' method."@6328..6354
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6354..6355
        WHITESPACE: "    "@6355..6359
        TEXT_LINE: "``fvec``"@6359..6367
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6367..6368
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6368..6376
        TEXT_LINE: "The residual values evaluated at the solution, for a 1-D `sigma`"@6376..6440
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6440..6441
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6441..6449
        TEXT_LINE: "this is ``(f(x, *popt) - ydata)/sigma``."@6449..6489
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6489..6490
        WHITESPACE: "    "@6490..6494
        TEXT_LINE: "``fjac``"@6494..6502
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6502..6503
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6503..6511
        TEXT_LINE: "A permutation of the R matrix of a QR"@6511..6548
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6548..6549
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6549..6557
        TEXT_LINE: "factorization of the final approximate"@6557..6595
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6595..6596
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6596..6604
        TEXT_LINE: "Jacobian matrix, stored column wise."@6604..6640
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6640..6641
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6641..6649
        TEXT_LINE: "Together with ipvt, the covariance of the"@6649..6690
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6690..6691
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6691..6699
        TEXT_LINE: "estimate can be approximated."@6699..6728
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6728..6729
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6729..6737
        TEXT_LINE: "Method 'lm' only provides this information."@6737..6780
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6780..6781
        WHITESPACE: "    "@6781..6785
        TEXT_LINE: "``ipvt``"@6785..6793
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6793..6794
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6794..6802
        TEXT_LINE: "An integer array of length N which defines"@6802..6844
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6844..6845
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6845..6853
        TEXT_LINE: "a permutation matrix, p, such that"@6853..6887
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6887..6888
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6888..6896
        TEXT_LINE: "fjac*p = q*r, where r is upper triangular"@6896..6937
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6937..6938
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6938..6946
        TEXT_LINE: "with diagonal elements of nonincreasing"@6946..6985
        NEWLINE: "\n"@6985..6986
        WHITESPACE: "        "@6986..6994
        TEXT_LINE: "magnitude. Column j of p is column ipvt(j)"@6994..7036
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7036..7037
        WHITESPACE: "        "@7037..7045
        TEXT_LINE: "of the identity matrix."@7045..7068
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7068..7069
        WHITESPACE: "        "@7069..7077
        TEXT_LINE: "Method 'lm' only provides this information."@7077..7120
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7120..7121
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7121..7125
        TEXT_LINE: "``qtf``"@7125..7132
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7132..7133
        WHITESPACE: "        "@7133..7141
        TEXT_LINE: "The vector (transpose(q) * fvec)."@7141..7174
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7174..7175
        WHITESPACE: "        "@7175..7183
        TEXT_LINE: "Method 'lm' only provides this information."@7183..7226
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7226..7227
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7227..7228
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7228..7232
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 1.9"@7232..7253
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7253..7254
    ENTRY@7254..7392 {
      NAME: "mesg"@7254..7258
      WHITESPACE: " "@7258..7259
      COLON: ":"@7259..7260
      WHITESPACE: " "@7260..7261
      TYPE: "str (returned only if `full_output` is True)"@7261..7305
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7305..7306
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7306..7310
      DESCRIPTION@7310..7392 {
        TEXT_LINE: "A string message giving information about the solution."@7310..7365
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7365..7366
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7366..7367
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7367..7371
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 1.9"@7371..7392
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7392..7393
    ENTRY@7393..7670 {
      NAME: "ier"@7393..7396
      WHITESPACE: " "@7396..7397
      COLON: ":"@7397..7398
      WHITESPACE: " "@7398..7399
      TYPE: "int (returned only if `full_output` is True)"@7399..7443
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7443..7444
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7444..7448
      DESCRIPTION@7448..7670 {
        TEXT_LINE: "An integer flag. If it is equal to 1, 2, 3 or 4, the solution was"@7448..7513
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7513..7514
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7514..7518
        TEXT_LINE: "found. Otherwise, the solution was not found. In either case, the"@7518..7583
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7583..7584
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7584..7588
        TEXT_LINE: "optional output variable `mesg` gives more information."@7588..7643
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7643..7644
        BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7644..7645
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7645..7649
        TEXT_LINE: ".. versionadded:: 1.9"@7649..7670
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@7670..7671
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7671..7672
  SECTION@7672..8001 {
    SECTION_HEADER@7672..7685 {
      NAME: "Raises"@7672..7678
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7678..7679
      UNDERLINE: "------"@7679..7685
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7685..7686
    ENTRY@7686..7784 {
      TYPE: "ValueError"@7686..7696
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7696..7697
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7697..7701
      DESCRIPTION@7701..7784 {
        TEXT_LINE: "if either `ydata` or `xdata` contain NaNs, or if incompatible options"@7701..7770
        NEWLINE: "\n"@7770..7771
        WHITESPACE: "    "@7771..7775
        TEXT_LINE: "are used."@7775..7784
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7784..7785
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7785..7786
    ENTRY@7786..7843 {
      TYPE: "RuntimeError"@7786..7798
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7798..7799
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7799..7803
      DESCRIPTION@7803..7843 {
        TEXT_LINE: "if the least-squares minimization fails."@7803..7843
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7843..7844
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7844..7845
    ENTRY@7845..7926 {
      TYPE: "TypeError"@7845..7854
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7854..7855
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7855..7859
      DESCRIPTION@7859..7926 {
        TEXT_LINE: "if the number of data points is fewer than the number of parameters"@7859..7926
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@7926..7927
    BLANK_LINE: "\n"@7927..7928
    ENTRY@7928..8001 {
      TYPE: "OptimizeWarning"@7928..7943
      NEWLINE: "\n"@7943..7944
      WHITESPACE: "    "@7944..7948
      DESCRIPTION@7948..8001 {
        TEXT_LINE: "if covariance of the parameters can not be estimated."@7948..8001
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@8001..8002
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8002..8003
  SECTION@8003..8212 {
    SECTION_HEADER@8003..8020 {
      NAME: "See Also"@8003..8011
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8011..8012
      UNDERLINE: "--------"@8012..8020
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@8020..8021
    ENTRY@8021..8088 {
      NAME: "least_squares"@8021..8034
      WHITESPACE: " "@8034..8035
      COLON: ":"@8035..8036
      WHITESPACE: " "@8036..8037
      DESCRIPTION@8037..8088 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Minimize the sum of squares of nonlinear functions."@8037..8088
      }
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@8088..8089
    ENTRY@8089..8212 {
      NAME: "scipy.stats.linregress"@8089..8111
      WHITESPACE: " "@8111..8112
      COLON: ":"@8112..8113
      WHITESPACE: " "@8113..8114
      DESCRIPTION@8114..8212 {
        TEXT_LINE: "Calculate a linear least squares regression for"@8114..8161
        NEWLINE: "\n"@8161..8162
        WHITESPACE: "                         "@8162..8187
        TEXT_LINE: "two sets of measurements."@8187..8212
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@8212..8213
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8213..8214
  SECTION@8214..9209 {
    SECTION_HEADER@8214..8225 {
      NAME: "Notes"@8214..8219
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8219..8220
      UNDERLINE: "-----"@8220..8225
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@8225..8226
    DESCRIPTION@8226..9209 {
      TEXT_LINE: "Users should ensure that inputs `xdata`, `ydata`, and the output of `f`"@8226..8297
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8297..8298
      TEXT_LINE: "are ``float64``, or else the optimization may return incorrect results."@8298..8369
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8369..8370
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8370..8371
      TEXT_LINE: "With ``method='lm'``, the algorithm uses the Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm"@8371..8445
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8445..8446
      TEXT_LINE: "through `leastsq`. Note that this algorithm can only deal with"@8446..8508
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8508..8509
      TEXT_LINE: "unconstrained problems."@8509..8532
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8532..8533
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8533..8534
      TEXT_LINE: "Box constraints can be handled by methods 'trf' and 'dogbox'. Refer to"@8534..8604
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8604..8605
      TEXT_LINE: "the docstring of `least_squares` for more information."@8605..8659
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8659..8660
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8660..8661
      TEXT_LINE: "Parameters to be fitted must have similar scale. Differences of multiple"@8661..8733
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8733..8734
      TEXT_LINE: "orders of magnitude can lead to incorrect results. For the 'trf' and"@8734..8802
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8802..8803
      TEXT_LINE: "'dogbox' methods, the `x_scale` keyword argument can be used to scale"@8803..8872
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8872..8873
      TEXT_LINE: "the parameters."@8873..8888
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8888..8889
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@8889..8890
      TEXT_LINE: "`curve_fit` is for local optimization of parameters to minimize the sum of squares"@8890..8972
      NEWLINE: "\n"@8972..8973
      TEXT_LINE: "of residuals. For global optimization, other choices of objective function, and"@8973..9052
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9052..9053
      TEXT_LINE: "other advanced features, consider using SciPy's :ref:`tutorial_optimize_global`"@9053..9132
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9132..9133
      TEXT_LINE: "tools or the `LMFIT <https://lmfit.github.io/lmfit-py/index.html>`_ package."@9133..9209
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@9209..9210
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9210..9211
  SECTION@9211..9447 {
    SECTION_HEADER@9211..9232 {
      NAME: "References"@9211..9221
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9221..9222
      UNDERLINE: "----------"@9222..9232
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@9232..9233
    CITATION@9233..9447 {
      DIRECTIVE_MARKER: ".."@9233..9235
      WHITESPACE: " "@9235..9236
      OPEN_BRACKET: "["@9236..9237
      LABEL: "1"@9237..9238
      CLOSE_BRACKET: "]"@9238..9239
      WHITESPACE: " "@9239..9240
      DESCRIPTION@9240..9447 {
        TEXT_LINE: "K. Vugrin et al. Confidence region estimation techniques for nonlinear"@9240..9310
        NEWLINE: "\n"@9310..9311
        WHITESPACE: "       "@9311..9318
        TEXT_LINE: "regression in groundwater flow: Three case studies. Water Resources"@9318..9385
        NEWLINE: "\n"@9385..9386
        WHITESPACE: "       "@9386..9393
        TEXT_LINE: "Research, Vol. 43, W03423, :doi:`10.1029/2005WR004804`"@9393..9447
      }
    }
  }
  NEWLINE: "\n"@9447..9448
  BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9448..9449
  SECTION@9449..12446 {
    SECTION_HEADER@9449..9466 {
      NAME: "Examples"@9449..9457
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9457..9458
      UNDERLINE: "--------"@9458..9466
    }
    NEWLINE: "\n"@9466..9467
    DESCRIPTION@9467..12446 {
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> import numpy as np"@9467..9489
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9489..9490
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"@9490..9525
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9525..9526
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> from scipy.optimize import curve_fit"@9526..9566
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9566..9567
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9567..9568
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> def func(x, a, b, c):"@9568..9593
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9593..9594
      TEXT_LINE: "...     return a * np.exp(-b * x) + c"@9594..9631
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9631..9632
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9632..9633
      TEXT_LINE: "Define the data to be fit with some noise:"@9633..9675
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9675..9676
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9676..9677
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> xdata = np.linspace(0, 4, 50)"@9677..9710
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9710..9711
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> y = func(xdata, 2.5, 1.3, 0.5)"@9711..9745
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9745..9746
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> rng = np.random.default_rng()"@9746..9779
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9779..9780
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> y_noise = 0.2 * rng.normal(size=xdata.size)"@9780..9827
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9827..9828
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> ydata = y + y_noise"@9828..9851
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9851..9852
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.plot(xdata, ydata, 'b-', label='data')"@9852..9898
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9898..9899
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9899..9900
      TEXT_LINE: "Fit for the parameters a, b, c of the function `func`:"@9900..9954
      NEWLINE: "\n"@9954..9955
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@9955..9956
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata)"@9956..10002
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10002..10003
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt"@10003..10011
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10011..10012
      TEXT_LINE: "array([2.56274217, 1.37268521, 0.47427475])"@10012..10055
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10055..10056
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.plot(xdata, func(xdata, *popt), 'r-',"@10056..10101
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10101..10102
      TEXT_LINE: "...          label='fit: a=%5.3f, b=%5.3f, c=%5.3f' % tuple(popt))"@10102..10168
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10168..10169
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10169..10170
      TEXT_LINE: "Constrain the optimization to the region of ``0 <= a <= 3``,"@10170..10230
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10230..10231
      TEXT_LINE: "``0 <= b <= 1`` and ``0 <= c <= 0.5``:"@10231..10269
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10269..10270
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10270..10271
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, bounds=(0, [3., 1., 0.5]))"@10271..10344
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10344..10345
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt"@10345..10353
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10353..10354
      TEXT_LINE: "array([2.43736712, 1.        , 0.34463856])"@10354..10397
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10397..10398
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.plot(xdata, func(xdata, *popt), 'g--',"@10398..10444
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10444..10445
      TEXT_LINE: "...          label='fit: a=%5.3f, b=%5.3f, c=%5.3f' % tuple(popt))"@10445..10511
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10511..10512
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10512..10513
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.xlabel('x')"@10513..10532
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10532..10533
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.ylabel('y')"@10533..10552
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10552..10553
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.legend()"@10553..10569
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10569..10570
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> plt.show()"@10570..10584
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10584..10585
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10585..10586
      TEXT_LINE: "For reliable results, the model `func` should not be overparametrized;"@10586..10656
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10656..10657
      TEXT_LINE: "redundant parameters can cause unreliable covariance matrices and, in some"@10657..10731
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10731..10732
      TEXT_LINE: "cases, poorer quality fits. As a quick check of whether the model may be"@10732..10804
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10804..10805
      TEXT_LINE: "overparameterized, calculate the condition number of the covariance matrix:"@10805..10880
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10880..10881
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10881..10882
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.linalg.cond(pcov)"@10882..10906
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10906..10907
      TEXT_LINE: "34.571092161547405  # may vary"@10907..10937
      NEWLINE: "\n"@10937..10938
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@10938..10939
      TEXT_LINE: "The value is small, so it does not raise much concern. If, however, we were"@10939..11014
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11014..11015
      TEXT_LINE: "to add a fourth parameter ``d`` to `func` with the same effect as ``a``:"@11015..11087
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11087..11088
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11088..11089
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> def func2(x, a, b, c, d):"@11089..11118
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11118..11119
      TEXT_LINE: "...     return a * d * np.exp(-b * x) + c  # a and d are redundant"@11119..11185
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11185..11186
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func2, xdata, ydata)"@11186..11233
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11233..11234
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.linalg.cond(pcov)"@11234..11258
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11258..11259
      TEXT_LINE: "1.13250718925596e+32  # may vary"@11259..11291
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11291..11292
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11292..11293
      TEXT_LINE: "Such a large value is cause for concern. The diagonal elements of the"@11293..11362
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11362..11363
      TEXT_LINE: "covariance matrix, which is related to uncertainty of the fit, gives more"@11363..11436
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11436..11437
      TEXT_LINE: "information:"@11437..11449
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11449..11450
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11450..11451
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> np.diag(pcov)"@11451..11468
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11468..11469
      TEXT_LINE: "array([1.48814742e+29, 3.78596560e-02, 5.39253738e-03, 2.76417220e+28])  # may vary"@11469..11552
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11552..11553
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11553..11554
      TEXT_LINE: "Note that the first and last terms are much larger than the other elements,"@11554..11629
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11629..11630
      TEXT_LINE: "suggesting that the optimal values of these parameters are ambiguous and"@11630..11702
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11702..11703
      TEXT_LINE: "that only one of these parameters is needed in the model."@11703..11760
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11760..11761
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11761..11762
      TEXT_LINE: "If the optimal parameters of `f` differ by multiple orders of magnitude, the"@11762..11838
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11838..11839
      TEXT_LINE: "resulting fit can be inaccurate. Sometimes, `curve_fit` can fail to find any"@11839..11915
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11915..11916
      TEXT_LINE: "results:"@11916..11924
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11924..11925
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@11925..11926
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> ydata = func(xdata, 500000, 0.01, 15)"@11926..11967
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11967..11968
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> try:"@11968..11976
      NEWLINE: "\n"@11976..11977
      TEXT_LINE: "...     popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, method = 'trf')"@11977..12043
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12043..12044
      TEXT_LINE: "... except RuntimeError as e:"@12044..12073
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12073..12074
      TEXT_LINE: "...     print(e)"@12074..12090
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12090..12091
      TEXT_LINE: "Optimal parameters not found: The maximum number of function evaluations is"@12091..12166
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12166..12167
      TEXT_LINE: "exceeded."@12167..12176
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12176..12177
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12177..12178
      TEXT_LINE: "If parameter scale is roughly known beforehand, it can be defined in"@12178..12246
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12246..12247
      TEXT_LINE: "`x_scale` argument:"@12247..12266
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12266..12267
      BLANK_LINE: "\n"@12267..12268
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, method = 'trf',"@12268..12330
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12330..12331
      TEXT_LINE: "...                        x_scale = [1000, 1, 1])"@12331..12381
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12381..12382
      TEXT_LINE: ">>> popt"@12382..12390
      NEWLINE: "\n"@12390..12391
      TEXT_LINE: "array([5.00000000e+05, 1.00000000e-02, 1.49999999e+01])"@12391..12446
    }
  }
}
=== EMIT ===
Use non-linear least squares to fit a function, f, to data.

Assumes ``ydata = f(xdata, *params) + eps``.

Parameters
----------
f : callable
    The model function, f(x, ...). It must take the independent
    variable as the first argument and the parameters to fit as
    separate remaining arguments.
xdata : array_like
    The independent variable where the data is measured.
    Should usually be an M-length sequence or an (k,M)-shaped array for
    functions with k predictors, and each element should be float
    convertible if it is an array like object.
ydata : array_like
    The dependent data, a length M array - nominally ``f(xdata, ...)``.
p0 : array_like, optional
    Initial guess for the parameters (length N). If None, then the
    initial values will all be 1 (if the number of parameters for the
    function can be determined using introspection, otherwise a
    ValueError is raised).
sigma : None or scalar or M-length sequence or MxM array, optional
    Determines the uncertainty in `ydata`. If we define residuals as
    ``r = ydata - f(xdata, *popt)``, then the interpretation of `sigma`
    depends on its number of dimensions:

    - A scalar or 1-D `sigma` should contain values of standard deviations of
      errors in `ydata`. In this case, the optimized function is
      ``chisq = sum((r / sigma) ** 2)``.

    - A 2-D `sigma` should contain the covariance matrix of
      errors in `ydata`. In this case, the optimized function is
      ``chisq = r.T @ inv(sigma) @ r``.

      .. versionadded:: 0.19

    None (default) is equivalent of 1-D `sigma` filled with ones.
absolute_sigma : bool, optional
    If True, `sigma` is used in an absolute sense and the estimated parameter
    covariance `pcov` reflects these absolute values.

    If False (default), only the relative magnitudes of the `sigma` values matter.
    The returned parameter covariance matrix `pcov` is based on scaling
    `sigma` by a constant factor. This constant is set by demanding that the
    reduced `chisq` for the optimal parameters `popt` when using the
    *scaled* `sigma` equals unity. In other words, `sigma` is scaled to
    match the sample variance of the residuals after the fit. Default is False.
    Mathematically,
    ``pcov(absolute_sigma=False) = pcov(absolute_sigma=True) * chisq(popt)/(M-N)``
check_finite : bool, optional
    If True, check that the input arrays do not contain nans of infs,
    and raise a ValueError if they do. Setting this parameter to
    False may silently produce nonsensical results if the input arrays
    do contain nans. Default is True if `nan_policy` is not specified
    explicitly and False otherwise.
bounds : 2-tuple of array_like or `Bounds`, optional
    Lower and upper bounds on parameters. Defaults to no bounds.
    There are two ways to specify the bounds:

    - Instance of `Bounds` class.

    - 2-tuple of array_like: Each element of the tuple must be either
      an array with the length equal to the number of parameters, or a
      scalar (in which case the bound is taken to be the same for all
      parameters). Use ``np.inf`` with an appropriate sign to disable
      bounds on all or some parameters.
method : {'lm', 'trf', 'dogbox'}, optional
    Method to use for optimization. See `least_squares` for more details.
    Default is 'lm' for unconstrained problems and 'trf' if `bounds` are
    provided. The method 'lm' won't work when the number of observations
    is less than the number of variables, use 'trf' or 'dogbox' in this
    case.

    .. versionadded:: 0.17
jac : callable, str or None, optional
    Function with signature ``jac(x, ...)`` which computes the Jacobian
    matrix of the model function with respect to parameters as a dense
    array_like structure. It will be scaled according to provided `sigma`.
    If None (default), the Jacobian will be estimated numerically.
    String keywords for 'trf' and 'dogbox' methods can be used to select
    a finite difference scheme, see `least_squares`.

    .. versionadded:: 0.18
full_output : bool, optional
    If True, this function returns additional information: `infodict`,
    `mesg`, and `ier`.

    .. versionadded:: 1.9
nan_policy : {'raise', 'omit', None}, optional
    Defines how to handle when input contains nan.
    The following options are available (default is None):

    * 'raise': throws an error
    * 'omit': performs the calculations ignoring nan values
    * None: no special handling of NaNs is performed
      (except what is done by check_finite); the behavior when NaNs
      are present is implementation-dependent and may change.

    Note that if this value is specified explicitly (not None),
    `check_finite` will be set as False.

    .. versionadded:: 1.11
**kwargs
    Keyword arguments passed to `leastsq` for ``method='lm'`` or
    `least_squares` otherwise.

Returns
-------
popt : array
    Optimal values for the parameters so that the sum of the squared
    residuals of ``f(xdata, *popt) - ydata`` is minimized.
pcov : 2-D array
    The estimated approximate covariance of popt. The diagonals provide
    the variance of the parameter estimate. To compute one standard
    deviation errors on the parameters, use
    ``perr = np.sqrt(np.diag(pcov))``. Note that the relationship between
    `cov` and parameter error estimates is derived based on a linear
    approximation to the model function around the optimum [1]_.
    When this approximation becomes inaccurate, `cov` may not provide an
    accurate measure of uncertainty.

    How the `sigma` parameter affects the estimated covariance
    depends on `absolute_sigma` argument, as described above.

    If the Jacobian matrix at the solution doesn't have a full rank, then
    'lm' method returns a matrix filled with ``np.inf``, on the other hand
    'trf'  and 'dogbox' methods use Moore-Penrose pseudoinverse to compute
    the covariance matrix. Covariance matrices with large condition numbers
    (e.g. computed with `numpy.linalg.cond`) may indicate that results are
    unreliable.
infodict : dict (returned only if `full_output` is True)
    a dictionary of optional outputs with the keys:

    ``nfev``
        The number of function calls. Methods 'trf' and 'dogbox' do not
        count function calls for numerical Jacobian approximation,
        as opposed to 'lm' method.
    ``fvec``
        The residual values evaluated at the solution, for a 1-D `sigma`
        this is ``(f(x, *popt) - ydata)/sigma``.
    ``fjac``
        A permutation of the R matrix of a QR
        factorization of the final approximate
        Jacobian matrix, stored column wise.
        Together with ipvt, the covariance of the
        estimate can be approximated.
        Method 'lm' only provides this information.
    ``ipvt``
        An integer array of length N which defines
        a permutation matrix, p, such that
        fjac*p = q*r, where r is upper triangular
        with diagonal elements of nonincreasing
        magnitude. Column j of p is column ipvt(j)
        of the identity matrix.
        Method 'lm' only provides this information.
    ``qtf``
        The vector (transpose(q) * fvec).
        Method 'lm' only provides this information.

    .. versionadded:: 1.9
mesg : str (returned only if `full_output` is True)
    A string message giving information about the solution.

    .. versionadded:: 1.9
ier : int (returned only if `full_output` is True)
    An integer flag. If it is equal to 1, 2, 3 or 4, the solution was
    found. Otherwise, the solution was not found. In either case, the
    optional output variable `mesg` gives more information.

    .. versionadded:: 1.9

Raises
------
ValueError
    if either `ydata` or `xdata` contain NaNs, or if incompatible options
    are used.
RuntimeError
    if the least-squares minimization fails.
TypeError
    if the number of data points is fewer than the number of parameters
OptimizeWarning
    if covariance of the parameters can not be estimated.

See Also
--------
least_squares : Minimize the sum of squares of nonlinear functions.
scipy.stats.linregress : Calculate a linear least squares regression for
two sets of measurements.

Notes
-----
Users should ensure that inputs `xdata`, `ydata`, and the output of `f`
are ``float64``, or else the optimization may return incorrect results.

With ``method='lm'``, the algorithm uses the Levenberg-Marquardt algorithm
through `leastsq`. Note that this algorithm can only deal with
unconstrained problems.

Box constraints can be handled by methods 'trf' and 'dogbox'. Refer to
the docstring of `least_squares` for more information.

Parameters to be fitted must have similar scale. Differences of multiple
orders of magnitude can lead to incorrect results. For the 'trf' and
'dogbox' methods, the `x_scale` keyword argument can be used to scale
the parameters.

`curve_fit` is for local optimization of parameters to minimize the sum of squares
of residuals. For global optimization, other choices of objective function, and
other advanced features, consider using SciPy's :ref:`tutorial_optimize_global`
tools or the `LMFIT <https://lmfit.github.io/lmfit-py/index.html>`_ package.

References
----------
.. [1] K. Vugrin et al. Confidence region estimation techniques for nonlinear
    regression in groundwater flow: Three case studies. Water Resources
    Research, Vol. 43, W03423, :doi:`10.1029/2005WR004804`

Examples
--------
>>> import numpy as np
>>> import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
>>> from scipy.optimize import curve_fit

>>> def func(x, a, b, c):
...     return a * np.exp(-b * x) + c

Define the data to be fit with some noise:

>>> xdata = np.linspace(0, 4, 50)
>>> y = func(xdata, 2.5, 1.3, 0.5)
>>> rng = np.random.default_rng()
>>> y_noise = 0.2 * rng.normal(size=xdata.size)
>>> ydata = y + y_noise
>>> plt.plot(xdata, ydata, 'b-', label='data')

Fit for the parameters a, b, c of the function `func`:

>>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata)
>>> popt
array([2.56274217, 1.37268521, 0.47427475])
>>> plt.plot(xdata, func(xdata, *popt), 'r-',
...          label='fit: a=%5.3f, b=%5.3f, c=%5.3f' % tuple(popt))

Constrain the optimization to the region of ``0 <= a <= 3``,
``0 <= b <= 1`` and ``0 <= c <= 0.5``:

>>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, bounds=(0, [3., 1., 0.5]))
>>> popt
array([2.43736712, 1.        , 0.34463856])
>>> plt.plot(xdata, func(xdata, *popt), 'g--',
...          label='fit: a=%5.3f, b=%5.3f, c=%5.3f' % tuple(popt))

>>> plt.xlabel('x')
>>> plt.ylabel('y')
>>> plt.legend()
>>> plt.show()

For reliable results, the model `func` should not be overparametrized;
redundant parameters can cause unreliable covariance matrices and, in some
cases, poorer quality fits. As a quick check of whether the model may be
overparameterized, calculate the condition number of the covariance matrix:

>>> np.linalg.cond(pcov)
34.571092161547405  # may vary

The value is small, so it does not raise much concern. If, however, we were
to add a fourth parameter ``d`` to `func` with the same effect as ``a``:

>>> def func2(x, a, b, c, d):
...     return a * d * np.exp(-b * x) + c  # a and d are redundant
>>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func2, xdata, ydata)
>>> np.linalg.cond(pcov)
1.13250718925596e+32  # may vary

Such a large value is cause for concern. The diagonal elements of the
covariance matrix, which is related to uncertainty of the fit, gives more
information:

>>> np.diag(pcov)
array([1.48814742e+29, 3.78596560e-02, 5.39253738e-03, 2.76417220e+28])  # may vary

Note that the first and last terms are much larger than the other elements,
suggesting that the optimal values of these parameters are ambiguous and
that only one of these parameters is needed in the model.

If the optimal parameters of `f` differ by multiple orders of magnitude, the
resulting fit can be inaccurate. Sometimes, `curve_fit` can fail to find any
results:

>>> ydata = func(xdata, 500000, 0.01, 15)
>>> try:
...     popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, method = 'trf')
... except RuntimeError as e:
...     print(e)
Optimal parameters not found: The maximum number of function evaluations is
exceeded.

If parameter scale is roughly known beforehand, it can be defined in
`x_scale` argument:

>>> popt, pcov = curve_fit(func, xdata, ydata, method = 'trf',
...                        x_scale = [1000, 1, 1])
>>> popt
array([5.00000000e+05, 1.00000000e-02, 1.49999999e+01])
